.TH TIME(1),User Commands,TIME(1)

.SH NAME
time - measure how long a command takes to run

.SH SYNOPSIS
time command [arg ...]

.SH DESCRIPTION
time runs command with the given arguments via shell -c, waits for it to finish, and prints the elapsed wall-clock time to standard error.

The arguments are joined with single spaces and handed to shell(1), so shell quoting, pipelines, and redirections are honoured.

After the command exits, time writes the elapsed time on its own line in the format:

MmSS.sss

where M is minutes (no leading zero), SS is seconds, and sss is a 3-digit fractional component derived from jiffies.

The target command's own stdout and stderr are not redirected;
the timing line is printed to stderr after the command returns so it does not interleave with normal output when stdout is captured.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: Always.
time reports its own exit rather than propagating the exit status of the timed command.

.SH BUGS
Elapsed time only tracks jiffies, seconds, and minutes.
A command that runs across an hour boundary will report an incorrect minutes field.

.SH SEE ALSO
date(1), sleep(1)
